The article discusses the importance of National Native American Heritage Month in the United States and highlights the contributions and challenges faced by Native Americans. It acknowledges the historical injustices and inequities experienced by Native Americans, including the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic. The article emphasizes the commitment of the Biden administration to advancing equity and opportunity for Native Americans, including significant funding for Indian Country through the American Rescue Plan. It also mentions the administration's efforts to involve Tribal Nations in infrastructure development and clean energy initiatives. The article recognizes the service and sacrifice of Native American veterans and calls for honoring Native American heritage and fulfilling the promise of the nation. Finally, it proclaims November 2021 as National Native American Heritage Month and designates November 26, 2021, as Native American Heritage Day.